 Because mosaicity, beam divergence, wavelength spread, incidence-angle uncertainty, detector-pixel size, and finite integration width all broaden the effective scattering condition, the projected coordinate should not be interpreted as an ideal reciprocal-space cut from a single perfect crystallite. The profiles are detector-derived, resolution-limited observables. The detector-pixel contribution to the transformed-coordinate uncertainty is discussed in Sec.~\ref{sec:projection_uncertainty}: the radial angular term remains bounded, while the azimuthal term becomes important mainly near the low-$2\theta$ specular limit. The ordered-film profiles are therefore interpreted through the projection itself, not through an assumption that each plotted point is an exact point in reciprocal space. The comparison remains meaningful because the calculated image is subjected to the same projection, binning, and resolution effects before it is compared with the measured profile.
 
-In Fig.~\ref{fig:ordered_chalcogenide_validation}, the off-specular $HK$ and $HK=0$ profiles play complementary roles. The off-specular arcs check the 2D-powder reciprocal-space construction and calibrated detector geometry, while their widths and asymmetries constrain the Gaussian-like mosaic core and instrumental resolution. The off-condition $HK=0$ peaks test the Lorentzian tail and show why a rapidly decaying mosaic core alone is insufficient. The bandwidth-sensitive $003$ morphology isolated in Fig.~\ref{fig:hk0_l3_star} reinforces that the forward model must include finite wavelength bandwidth explicitly. 
